As jeremy wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/21/2004 at 23:06:46 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>In a recent test, we were asked to solve an equation
>n!/[(n-6)!] = n!/[(n-4)!] * 4!/(2!), which although others used 
>trial and error for, I attempted to solve algebraically.
>
>[Difficulty]
>After reducing the equation by eliminating n! and (n-6)! a quadratic 
>in n is found, giving n=1, 8
>But having n=1 gives an (n-6)! = (-5)! which, as I have seen in the 
>forums is impossible. 
>
>[Thoughts]
>n!/[(n-6)!] = n!/[(n-4)!] * 4!/(2!)
>therefore: n!/(n!) = (n-6)!/[(n-4)!] * 12
>therefore: 1 = (n-6)!/[(n-4)(n-5)(n-6)!] * 12
>therefore by cancelling (n-6)! : 1 = 1/[(n-4)(n-5)] * 12
>therefore (n-4)(n-5)=12
>hence: n^2 - 9n - 8 = 0 --> n=8, 1
>So there is my problem, in that (1-6)! = (-5)! = undefined.
>
>Perhaps the problem lies in that allowing n=1 to be a solution gives 
>a negative times a negative to = positive 12 (in the quadratic). 
>Maybe this is not true of negative factorials IF they were to exist. 
>Or is the question simply a matter of ignoring the possibility of 
>having a negative factorial altogether, hence eliminating n=1?
>

Nice golng, Jeremy.  Your work shows correctly that n = 8 and n = 1 are the only 
possible solutions.  As your last remark suggests, n = 1 can be eliminated since the 
factorials of negative numbers are not defined.  n = 8, on the other hand, works, as you 
can verify directly.  


